Steno dictionary source for a Plover plugin, defining JS/TS code-generation snippets triggered by stroke chords. Parsed by `src/parse.ts` — the template syntax here (`%0-9`, `%d`, `%t`, `%b`, `%p`, `%[...|...%]`, `%(EXPR)`) is that parser's contract; changing the operator set or escape rules requires updating parse.ts in lockstep. This file is the migration target replacing `snippets.txt`.

Structure: each entry is a stroke on a code-fence open line (```` ````STROKE ````) with the template body between fences, optionally preceded by a `###` display-name comment and followed by directives (`@count KEYS`, `@arity N`, `@multiline`, `@fuse`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@literal`) that apply to the entry immediately above. `#`/`//` lines are comments, dropped by the parser.

Key semantics an editor must preserve: `%d` is a literal digit substitution (the count, or loop index inside `%[...%]`), never a tabstop — conflating it with `%0-9` landing points breaks tabstop numbering. `%(EXPR)` computes a landing point position linearly in `d` with no renumbering, so overlapping `%(EXPR)` results across entries is a hard parse error, not a warning. `@fuse` entries (function-family strokes like `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT`) merge a return-type stroke into the base shape so no untyped intermediate stroke is required — this is what lets `func / TPH-FLT` resolve directly to a typed function. `@count KEYS` (e.g. `@count AOE`, `@count AO`) binds a steno key-bank to the repeat count for `%[...%]` blocks; the bank choice (AOE vs AO) determines the max arity representable (3 vs fewer) — the params section explicitly notes typed params cap at 3 via the AO bank. `@type`/`@arity N`/`@noarg` mark the secondary "type" strokes (TPH=number, PR=Promise<%t> arity 1, PH=Map<%t,%t> arity 2, etc.) as non-terminal until N type-args are appended — `STKWR-T` is the standalone type-emitter that lets any of these compose freestanding (e.g., `STKWR-T/PR/STR` → `Promise<string>`). `@literal` entries (the data-structure classes) are emitted verbatim with no tabstops or substitution — whitespace/newlines in those bodies are literal output, not `%b`-controlled.

Coupling: the entire template DSL (operator list, escape set, directive names) is a contract with `src/parse.ts`; any new operator or directive added here is inert until parse.ts recognizes it. The data-structures section's "untyped selector-variant" (stripping `<T>` and `: T`) is described in a comment but not shown here — verify parse.ts or a sibling file implements that stripping if it's expected to exist. Method-family strokes (array/string/math methods, `STKWR*PLT/...`) rely on a shared root+selector convention where the `D` suffix forces a block body — that convention is comment-documented here only, not enforced by fence syntax itself.